items.title: NATO chief avoids talk of Ukraine's membership, says priority is helping Kyiv defend itself
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
NATO Secretary-General Mark Rutte on Tuesday sidestepped questions about Ukraine’s possible membership of the military alliance, saying that the priority now must be to strengthen the country’s hand in any future peace talks with Russia. items.title: Timothée Chalamet and Zendaya win at Gotham Awards

items.content:

items.title: Floods wreak havoc in Malaysia and Thailand; over 30 killed
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Severe floods caused by monsoon rains killed more than 30 people and displaced tens of thousands in Malaysia and southern Thailand, officials said Tuesday, with both countries preparing shelters and evacuation plans in anticipation of more heavy rain. (AP Video by Syawalludin Zain). Read more: https://bit.ly/4ihQpRl

items.title: South Korean president declares martial law, accusing opposition of anti-state activity
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:

items.title: LIVE: Anti-government protest in Tbilisi, Georgia
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
Anti-government protesters demonstrate outside the Georgian parliament in Tbilisi. Over 200 people were detained during the previous nights of protests against the government’s decision to suspend negotiations to join the European Union.

items.title: King Charles III welcomes Qatar's Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani for UK visit
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
King Charles III formally welcomed the emir of Qatar, Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani, on Tuesday as part of his two-day visit to the UK. The Princess of Wales, Kate, and Prince William greeted Sheikh Tamim and his wife, Sheikha Jawaher bint Hamad bin Suhaim Al Thani, earlier on Tuesday before the couples travelled to Horse Guards Parade in central London where Charles formally welcomed them. items.title: People block military vehicle trying to leave area near South Korea's parliament
items.author: Associated Press
items.content:
People were seen blocking a military vehicle as it tried to leave an area near South Korea's parliament late Tuesday. Protesters gathered in front of the Parliament building after South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol declared martial law, vowing to eliminate “anti-state” forces as he struggles against an opposition that controls the country’s parliament and that he accuses of sympathizing with communist North Korea. Read more: https://bit.ly/4imbrP5
